[normal]1.1[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The [bold]‘[bold]Nicholson Challenge’[bold] in 2012–13[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]By the end of the 
[normal]2010
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]pending 
[normal]R
[normal]eview period (
[normal]covering 
[normal]2011
[normal]–12
[normal] to 2014
[normal]–15
[normal]) the NHS will have received more than £12.
[normal]7
[normal] billion of increased funding, but it will still face significant additional demand for services arising from demographic change, public expectations and pressures to fund new technologies and d
[normal]rugs. To meet this challenge the NHS needs to secure up to £20 billion of efficiency savings by 2014
[normal]–15
[normal], and will have to keep delivering efficiency savings o
[normal]f a similar scale 
[normal]in 2015
[normal]–16
[normal] 
[normal]and beyond
[normal].
[normal]QIPP [bold]delivery in 2011–12 and 2012–13[bold]2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the first two ye
[normal]ars of the QIPP delivery period, the NHS has delivered in line with its forecast efficiency savings, with 
[normal]primary care trusts (
[normal]PCTs
[normal])
[normal] reporting delivery of £5.8 billion savings in 2011–12 and a further £5.0 billion in 2012–13.
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]While this is an encouraging p
[normal]erformance through the first half of the QIPP delivery period, it will require concerted effort across the health system to maintain delivery over the second half of the period in a sustainable way that prepares the NHS for continuing financial challenges 
[normal]in 2013–14 and 
[normal]beyond 
[normal]discussed in section 1.2
[normal].
[normal]4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]While 
[normal]delivering savings of £10.8 billion over two years, the NHS has maintained its strong overall performance on key measures on hospital-acquired infections, ambulance response and overall A&amp;E performance
[normal].
[normal] Evidence shows
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In response to the 
[normal]diff
[normal]iculties 
[normal]A&amp;E 
[normal]faced during quarter 4 
[normal]t
[normal]he Department has 
[normal]taken early action by 
[normal]earmarking 
[normal]£500
[normal] 
[normal]m
[normal]illion
[normal] to 
[normal]ensure staff have the support they need during the next 
[normal]two
[normal] 
[normal]winter
[normal]s
[normal] and that patients are not left facing excessive waits for treatment.
[normal] Prof
[normal]essor 
[normal]Sir B
[normal]ruce Keogh 
[normal]is 
[normal]carry
[normal]ing
[normal] out a review 
[normal]of urgent and emergency care l
[normal]ook
[normal]ing
[normal] at the demands on services and how the NHS should respond in the long term.
[normal]1.2[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The challenge in 2013–14 and beyond[bold]6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]NHS staff are improving their productivity: according to Office for National Statistics figures, between 
[normal]the years 
[normal]2000 and 2
[normal]010, labour productivity in healthcare rose faster than in the economy as a whole.  In particular, the NHS has responded well to the QIPP challenge. NHS staff across the country are using the opportunity that QIPP provides to improve services.  A few examp
[normal]les of the improvements underway are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]QIPP plans for 2013–14 are expected to deliver savings of £4.2 billion. Based on the latest results (August 2013), NHS England expects to deliver £4.0 billion in 2013–14, 5% below the target. This was split between provide
[normal]r productivity savings delivered through the tariff reduction in contracts (£2.2 billion planned) and CCG/direct commissioning (£2.0 billion planned):
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The shortfall 
[normal]in QIPP impacts on the overall financial performance of NHS England. From an assessment of risks and mitigations for the current financial year, NHS England has identified a continued imbalance of financial risk between individual CCGs and between CCGs and
[normal] direct commissioning, with the direct commissioning financial position being the more fragile. In year the risks have been largely mitigated; however, whil
[normal]e
[normal] the risks arising have a recurrent impact into future years the sources of mitigation are largely non-recurrent.
[normal]Departmental efficiency plans[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Pay restraint is an important part of the Government’s strategy to meet the current economic and fiscal challen
[normal]ges while maintaining services and jobs. The Government has set clear expectations on pay restraint across the public services, with public sector pay awards averaging up to 1% in 2013–14 and 2014–15. The 2013 Budget confirmed that public sector pay awards
[normal] in 2015–16 will be limited to an average of up to 1%, and the 
[normal]2013 S
[normal]pending 
[normal]Review
[normal] confirmed the cross-government commitment to reducing the cost of progression pay in public services, including the NHS. In the longer term, of course, pay trends will be d
[normal]ependent on wider economic factors.
[normal]10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Employers want to secure a better balance between pay, performance and productivity. To deliver 
[normal]the
[normal] aspirations for the prevention of ill
[normal]-
[normal]health and the delivery of seven
[normal]-
[normal]day care, national pay frameworks must be fit for
[normal] purpose, fair to staff and offer the taxpayer the very best value for money. The NHS will be in a stronger position to maintain or increase staffing levels, and therefore protect jobs, if employers are able to make better use of their pay bill.
[normal]11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Govern
[normal]ment has 
[normal]therefore invited the NHS Pay Review Body to consider, if they believe an award is justified, how any such award might be made dependent on the partners (NHS Staff Council) reaching agreement on further Agenda for Change (AfC) reform. In particula
[normal]r, how in the current economic climate and within the context of the overall expenditure on pay and pensions, AfC might be made more affordable. 
[normal]It is 
[normal]proposed that any such recommendation is tied to progress on AfC reform, with the parties invited to repo
[normal]rt on progress in their evidence to the NHS
[normal] 
[normal]P
[normal]ay 
[normal]R
[normal]eview 
[normal]B
[normal]ody
[normal] next year, effectively deferring any award.
[normal]12
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]However, it is recognised that to meet the efficiency challenge the NHS needs to deliver recurrent efficiency savings of up to £20 billion by 2014–15. T
[normal]his means that any one-off savings will need to be replaced with other sources of savings in subsequent years. The National Audit Office has confirmed that the vast majority (over 90%) of efficiency savings delivered to date are recurrent
[normal].
[normal]13
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the reformed
[normal] health system, all organisations will have a role to play in driving the required efficiency improvements, with NHS England having a particularly crucial responsibility. Ensuring the delivery of QIPP was built into NHS England’s authorisation and planning
[normal] processes for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs).
[normal]14
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The strong NHS QIPP performance since 2011–12, which is continuing into 2013–14, gives a firm foundation for sustained delivery over the rest of this Spending Review period, against a backdrop of on-goin
[normal]g challenges from rising demands for NHS services
[normal].
[normal]15
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department is also taking action centrally to support the NHS to deliver the sustained savings that are needed.
[normal]16
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In August 2013,  the Department published its strategy for holding NHS spending on non-pa
[normal]y items flat over the next three years
[normal], which w
[normal]ould 
[normal]see procurement and agency spend across the NHS reduced by £1.5 billion in real terms by the end of 2015–16
[normal], t
[normal]hus helping the NHS meet both the current QIPP challenge and the efficiency challenge in 2015
[normal]–16 and beyond.
[normal]The financial challenge[bold]17
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 2010 
[normal]Spending Review set the NHS a challenge to deliver up to £20
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illion
[normal] of annual efficiency savings by 2014
[normal]–15
[normal]. The budgets announced in the 
[normal]s
[normal]pending 
[normal]r
[normal]ound in July 
[normal]2013 
[normal]make clear that the financial challeng
[normal]e will be even greater in 2015
[normal]–16
[normal].
[normal] Given the financial situation, more efficiencies will be needed in future years: 
[normal]in 
[normal]summer
[normal] 2013
[normal], NHS England published its Call to Action
[normal], which estimated that the NHS would need to make £30
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n of savings between 
[normal]2014
[normal]–15
[normal] and 2020
[normal]–21
[normal]. This extended period of significant savings requirements has important consequences for the need to embrace transformational change to secure sustainability.
[normal]Improving outcomes for patients[bold]18
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Even within this challenging efficiency req
[normal]uirement, NHS England is determined to place improving outcomes for patients at the heart of their work, and to do its part in meeting the challenges which have been laid out by the Francis, Keogh and Berwick reviews of the NHS. For that reason, commission
[normal]ers are expected to prioritise an approach to planning which combines transparency with detailed patient and public participation. 
[normal]There n
[normal]eed to 
[normal]be
[normal], from the bottom up, quantifiable ambitions for each domain
[normal] of the NHS Outcomes Framework.
[normal]19
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]NHS England will 
[normal]therefore be asking CCGs and Area Teams to work together to determine local levels of ambition, based on evidence of local patient and public benefit, against a common set of indicators that place 
[normal]the
[normal] duty to tackle health inequalities front and centre sta
[normal]ge. This will ensure that the improvements 
[normal]NHS England is 
[normal]aiming to deliver for patients
[normal],
[normal] across 
[normal]eight
[normal] key areas
[normal], are clearly articulated:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The need for transformational change[bold]20
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]NHS England is continuing to focus attention on the QIPP challenge in order to maintain or improve the quality of healthcare services in a c
[normal]onstrained funding 
[normal]environment.
[normal]21
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As the previous section shows, QIPP has so far not met its targets for transformational change, which is vital for the financial sustainability of the NHS in the long term. QIPP savings so far have been weighted towards central actions, includ
[normal]ing pay and administrative cost reductions and tactical efficiency programmes. The NHS cannot rely on pay restraint and reductions in the unit cost of care to deliver QIPP-scale efficiencies in the
[normal] long term.
[normal]22
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To address this, NHS England has increased the 
[normal]system’s focus on transformational change.  From 2013
[normal]–14
[normal] onwards, QIPP plans for CCGs and NHS England’s direct commissioners are broken down between transactional schemes (where savings are expected to be achieved through productivity 
[normal]and contractual savin
[normal]gs) and transformational schemes such as service re-design and pathway changes. In 2013
[normal]–14
[normal], the transformational schemes represent 44% of the total QIPP target for CCGs and direct commissioners (£0.9 billion). The latest data (from August) shows that £0.2 
[normal]billion (22% of the planned savings) had already been delivered and NHS England forecasts that £0.7 billion (78% of the planned savings) will be achieved by the end of the year. The shortfall on transformational schemes account for the vast majority of the
[normal] total forecast QIPP shortfall. QIPP performance is measured against phased plans on a monthly basis as part of t
[normal]he NHS England finance report.
[normal]23
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Doing
[normal] better on procurement, productivity and transforming care pathways
[normal] is a must
[normal].  
[normal]I
[normal]mproving procurement will 
[normal]be a vital contribution to sustainable efficiency savings.  The Department of Health announced a new strategy for NHS procurement in August
[normal] 2013 (see footnote 
[normal]2
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]24
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Improvements in workforce productivity are key to helping deliver the efficiency savings in t
[normal]his, and the next, spending round period. So far, workforce productivity gains have contributed 12% of the total savings made in 2011–12 and 2012–13, compared with 23% which has come from pay restraint. The workforce productivity share of total savings is 
[normal]expected to grow to 26% in 2013–14 and 2014–15. Despite improved productivity performance in the last two years, there still exists wide labour productivity variation at provider level. Levelling up performance as well as shifting the average provider perf
[normal]ormance upwards will help achieve the workforce produ
[normal]ctivity gains that are needed.
[normal]25
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Where activity has fallen so far, this is more due to contractual levers than to changing the way 
[normal]the NHS
[normal] deliver
[normal]s
[normal] care. To turn this increased productivity into savings, p
[normal]roviders as well as processes
[normal] will need to transform
[normal], moving more care out of hospitals.  
[normal]T
[normal]ransform
[normal]ing
[normal] the way in which health and social care services are delivered, using available resources more effectively and focusing on integrated care and prevention
[normal] to improve patient outcomes and experience
[normal] is required
[normal].
[normal]26
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department and NHS England have a key role to play in setting out and driving the case for transformational change. For example, the Secretary of State has challenged the NHS to go ‘paperless’ by
[normal] 2018, highlighting the potential benefits for patients and for taxpayers. The Mandate to NHS England set objectives for it to lead the health and care system in driving better integration of services; and the Government will hold NHS England to account fo
[normal]r its performance. However, this transformation cannot be imposed from the top. Engagement on specific local service changes needs to be locally led, and it is CCGs and their local partners that are best placed to understand the needs of their communities 
[normal]and the
[normal] opportunities for improvement.
[normal]27
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is vital for organisations to work collaboratively to communicate the case for transformational change and to deliver it: both to benefit patients and to improve efficiency. Continued protection of health funding d
[normal]oes not mean that all services should remain unchanged. The NHS must adapt and evolve 
[normal]to meet the challenges of future demographic trends a
[normal]nd rising demand expectations.
[normal]28
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government’s modernisation of the NHS will enable commissioners to make changes th
[normal]at will deliver real improvements in quality through commissioning that is driven by clinical insight, patient choice and a focus on improving outcomes. This will promote greater integration of services at the local level, including a more coordinated appr
[normal]oach to assessment, care planning and care management. Together with increased patient choice and a more rigorous and transparent system for regulating providers, this modernisation will provide much stronger incentives and opportunities to deliver more in
[normal]tegrated, personalised and preventive care.
[normal]1.3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Delivering transformational change[bold]29
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]From 1 April 2013, NHS England and C
[normal]CGs 
[normal]are responsible for planning and commissioning health services in England. 
[normal]D
[normal]iagram
[normal] 
[normal]1
[normal] 
[normal]describes 
[normal]NHS England’s high-level plan to deliver 
[normal]the 
[normal]transformational change
[normal] necessary for financial stability while improving outcomes for patients.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Diagram
[normal] 
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A national debate[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]30
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recognising the need for transformational change, NHS England has published 
[normal]its Call to Action setting 
[normal]out the scale of the challenge facing the NHS through to 2020
[normal]–21,
[normal] and creat
[normal]ing
[normal] the basis for a national debate involving the public, charities, NHS staff
[normal] and experts on the future shape of the NHS. NHS England will support CCGs in responding to this debate whil
[normal]e
[normal] also drawing on its conclusions to form 
[normal]its 
[normal]strategy for the next ten years.
[normal]31
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]NHS England is also working with partner organisations including Moni
[normal]tor, the NHS Trust Development Authority
[normal] (TDA)
[normal], the L
[normal]ocal Government Association (L
[normal]GA
[normal])
[normal] and others to understand the implications of this challenge across local health and care systems.
[normal] 
[normal]Supporting commissioners[bold]32
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CCGs and NHS England’s direct commissioners
[normal] are best placed to identify the opportunities for transforming services.  NHS England is taking steps to
[normal] support their work, including:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]More broadly, developing, supporting and assuring the commissio
[normal]ning system is one of the core processes set out in the NHS England’s business plan. NHS England is committed to provide relevant and sufficient development support for each CCG to enable them to become excellent commissioners and equip them to meet the lo
[normal]cal and national ambitions for service improvement.  The CCG Development Framework was approved in July 2013.
[normal]34
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It was acknowledged within the framework that greater understanding of what makes a ‘great CCG’ was needed.  A series of different research and in
[normal]sight pieces have been commissioned, which include research into challenges to transformation; a review of international evidence; discussions with leading experts; and gathering and reviewing emerging best practice from CCGs themselves.  NHS England will 
[normal]publish the findings from this work 
[normal]in
[normal] autumn 
[normal]2013 
[normal]as a 
[normal]Framework of Excellence in Clinical Commissioning
[normal]. The framework will take the criteria tested during authorisation and puts them within the context of the wider research. CCGs are now considering the
[normal]ir development needs in the context of their capacity and capability to meet their local strategic plans for service improvement.
[normal]Key challenges[bold]35
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to achieve transformational change while delivering efficiencies, new community services can only be
[normal] funded by removing capacity from existing services.  It is vital that the NHS at all levels wins support from partners and t
[normal]he community for these changes.
[normal]36
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As part of 
[normal]the 
[normal]collective work on the Call for Action, 
[normal]NHS England is 
[normal]looking at how 
[normal]it
[normal] can reform 
[normal]the pricing and contracting systems to support transformational change. Starting from 1 April 2014 
[normal]NHS England 
[normal]ha
[normal]s
[normal] agreed with Monitor that the rules around variation to the national tariff are changed so that localities with ideas that can transform servi
[normal]ces for patients are not held back from doing so because of tariff constraints. Together with Monitor, 
[normal]it is 
[normal]also committed to publishing further thinking on what this could look like for 2015
[normal]–16 b
[normal]y the end of 
[normal]2013.
[normal]Integration [bold]T[bold]ransformation [bold]F[bold]und[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]37
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The financial settlement for 
[normal]20
[normal]15
[normal]–16
[normal] includes the creation of an 
[normal]I
[normal]ntegration 
[normal]T
[normal]ransformation 
[normal]F
[normal]und (ITF). This will see the establishment of a pooled budget of £3.8
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illion
[normal], which will be committed at local level with the agreement of 
[normal]h
[normal]ealth 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]w
[normal]ellbeing 
[normal]b
[normal]o
[normal]ards. Locally, CCGs can decide to place additional resources into the ITF if they wish. The ITF is a ‘game changer’: it creates a substantial ring-fenced budget for investment in out-of-hospital care. However, it will also require the NHS to make savings o
[normal]f over £2
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n in existing spending predominantly relating to acute care. This implies the need for an extra productivity gain of 
[normal]between 
[normal]2
[normal]%
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]3% across the NHS as a whole in 
[normal]20
[normal]15
[normal]–16
[normal], including any immediate ‘dividend’ from investments made under the 
[normal]ITF itself. NHS England will work with Monitor to determine how this is reflected in the expectations placed on commissioners (in the form of QIPP savings from demand management, pathway change, etc
[normal].
[normal]) and providers (in the form of the efficiency deflator i
[normal]ncorporated in tariff). NHS England is currently exploring the feasibility of bringing forward an element of the 
[normal]20
[normal]15
[normal]–16
[normal] saving requirement into 
[normal]20
[normal]14
[normal]–15
[normal] to avoid a financial ‘cliff edge’ 
[normal]in 2015–16
[normal].
[normal]38
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The NHS will only be sustainable in 
[normal]20
[normal]15
[normal]–16 
[normal]if the ITF 
[normal]is
[normal] put 
[normal]to the best possible use 
[normal]and 
[normal]reduce
[normal]s
[normal] significantly the demand for hospital services.  That investment could be targeted at a range of initiatives to develop out
[normal]-
[normal]of
[normal]-
[normal]hospital care, including early intervention, admission avoidance and early hospital dis
[normal]charge - taking advantage, for example, of new collaborative technologies to give patients more control of their care and transform the cost effectiveness of local services. This will require investment in social care and other 
[normal]l
[normal]ocal 
[normal]a
[normal]uthority services, pr
[normal]imary care services and community health services. Crucially, to access the ITF, 
[normal]h
[normal]ealth and 
[normal]w
[normal]ellbeing 
[normal]b
[normal]oards will need to agree a joint plan to transform services, taking account of the impact that plan will have on local NHS services and providers.
[normal]39
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A critical ingredient of success for the transformation fund will be the quality of partnership working at local level. Health 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]w
[normal]ellbeing 
[normal]b
[normal]oards will need to have strong governance arrangements for making transparent and evidence-based decisions about t
[normal]he use of the ITF. The Chief Executive of NHS England will remain the accounting officer for the ITF, accountable to 
[normal]P
[normal]arliament for its use, and in that context NHS England Area Directors will take a close interest in the effectiveness of local arrangement
[normal]s for governance and implementation.
[normal]1.4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The prospects for the long-term viability of NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts[bold]40
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Over £60
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n of the 
[normal]Department’s 
[normal]DEL (
[normal]Departmental Expenditure Limit
[normal])
[normal] is spent 
[normal]via NHS commissioners 
[normal]with NHS providers 
[normal]to 
[normal]provi
[normal]de
[normal] healthcare 
[normal]to the public
[normal]. If NHS 
[normal]p
[normal]rovider expenditure is more than this income, plus income from other sources, then this scores as a cost to the DEL
[normal],
[normal] and if it is less it is a benefit.
[normal]41
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The capital expenditure of NHS 
[normal]p
[normal]roviders
[normal], either financed through their cash surpluses or borrowing, also scores to the DEL.
[normal]42
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]NHS 
[normal]p
[normal]rovider surpluses and deficits
[normal],
[normal] and capital expenditure score to the DEL in the year that they occur. 
[normal]The Department
[normal] has to include a forecast of th
[normal]ese in its own fin
[normal]ancial plans.
[normal]Role of [bold]the Department[bold]43
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department
[normal] has taken the responsibility for funding the immediate deficit support needs of NHS trusts and NHS 
[normal]foundation trusts (F
[normal]Ts
[normal])
[normal]. However
[normal],
[normal] the 
[normal]D
[normal]epartment is clear that this funding will not be provided on an 
[normal]indefinite basis. The role of the 
[normal]D
[normal]epartment in providing this support is therefore to drive the development of permanent solutions to financial deficits by ensuring that trusts work with commission
[normal]er
[normal]s and the relevant regulators to develop timely, sustain
[normal]able solutions.
[normal]44
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the short term, financial support provided by the 
[normal]D
[normal]epartment will increase to support the individual deficits of 
[normal]NHS 
[normal]t
[normal]rusts and FT
[normal]s
[normal]. To provide the necessary challenge back to these organisations, the 
[normal]D
[normal]epartment is 
[normal]pu
[normal]tting mechanisms 
[normal]in place 
[normal]whereby access to deficit support is contingent on swift progress to develop sustainable solutions.
[normal]45
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the first 
[normal]instance
[normal] this will rely on the relevant regulators (TDA and Monitor) to drive the development of sustainable solutions and set clear t
[normal]erms and milestones aro
[normal]und the plans to develop these.
[normal]NHS [bold]t[bold]rusts and [bold]the [bold]role of [bold]TDA[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]46
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There has been a significant shift in the overall financial position of the NHS trust sector. In 
[normal]20
[normal]12
[normal]–13,
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]he NHS 
[normal]t
[normal]rust sector aggregate position was a net £106 million
[normal] surplus
[normal]:
[normal] with 97 out of 102 
[normal]t
[normal]rusts report
[normal]ing
[normal] a surplus or breakeven. As at month 4 of 
[normal]20
[normal]13
[normal]–14
[normal], 
[normal]the 
[normal]TDA ha
[normal]s
[normal] identified an aggregate forecast outturn deficit of £167 million
[normal]:
[normal] with 31 
[normal]t
[normal]rusts now forecasting an operating deficit at year end.
[normal]47
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The cause of this
[normal] deterioration has been put down to a combination of
[normal]:
[normal] a net price deflator
[normal];
[normal] a reduction in education and training funding
[normal]; and,
[normal] a commissioner rules-based approach resulting in a decrease in non
[normal]-
[normal]recurring income from 2012
[normal]–13
[normal]. Further analysis by 
[normal]the 
[normal]TDA ha
[normal]s estimated the reduction in non-recurring income to NHS trusts 
[normal]as
[normal] £281 million in 2013
[normal]–14
[normal].
[normal]48
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Non-recurring funding previously provided by 
[normal]strategic health authorities (
[normal]SHAs
[normal])
[normal] and 
[normal]primary care trusts (
[normal]PCTs
[normal])
[normal] often supported financial difficulties in trusts. As
[normal] a result
[normal],
[normal] the change in the outturn position is large
[normal]ly
[normal] due to increased transparency revealing the true underlying position of some organisations rather than a sudden worsening of the sustainability of organisations.
[normal] This also means that NHS trusts and F
[normal]Ts are treated in the same way.
[normal]49
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]TDA is charged with focusing on the organisations struggling to manage their finances. In most cases, the organisations in deficit are the same bodies which face financial challenges to become viable and meet the requirements 
[normal]to achieve FT status. The incr
[normal]eased transparency of finances presents a new opportunity to understand the underlying causes of these pressures which may 
[normal]have been previously concealed.
[normal]50
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]TDA is responsible for developing plans not only to overcome deficits but to take organisations t
[normal]o a point where they can integrated into 
[normal]the
[normal] FT land
[normal]scape.
[normal]51
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]One of the key functions of the TDA is to support the transition of the remaining 99 NHS 
[normal]t
[normal]rusts to FT status or to a
[normal]n alternative sustainable form.
[normal]52
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government wants NHS trusts to improve the qu
[normal]ality and sustainability of services as quickly as possible. It is vital that the focus on improving quality cannot be compromised by a focus on the pursuit of 
[normal]FT
[normal] status for its own sake. So where time is needed to make the necessary improvement, it is imp
[normal]ortant that the process is not rushed and that risks to patient care are not created.
[normal]53
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 2014 deadline for reaching 
[normal]FT
[normal] status has done much to galvanise the NHS trust sector and drive improvement. However, in light of Robert Francis’ report, 
[normal]the Departmen
[normal]t
[normal] ha
[normal]s
[normal] allowed the TDA to agree trajectories for NHS trusts to reach 
[normal]FT 
[normal]status or be 
[normal]moved
[normal] to an alternative
[normal], more
[normal] sustainable form, on timescales that go beyond 2014
[normal],
[normal] on a case by case basis. In so doing, 
[normal]this
[normal] will ensure that the primary focus of the TDA 
[normal]and of NHS trusts themselves is on improving the quality and sustainab
[normal]ility 
[normal]of services for patients
[normal].
[normal]NHS [bold]f[bold]oundation [bold]t[bold]rusts and [bold]the [bold]role of Monitor[bold]54
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
