[normal]3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]INTEGRATION OF[bold] HEALTH AND CARE SERVICES[bold]3.1[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services[bold]81
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Across health and care provision, services are often disjointed and poorly coordinated which causes distress for people who need care a
[normal]nd support as well as their families and carers. Disjointed care leads to poor experiences, worse outcomes and inefficiencies across the system. In contrast, better coordinated care, focused on individuals rather than traditional service boundaries, has th
[normal]e potential to improve services with positive impact on people’s experience, outcomes and on the efficiency of services.
[normal]82
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]However, while there is broad consensus that integration has the potential to deliver large benefits, evidence as to the effectiveness 
[normal]of specific schemes that the NHS and/or local authorities have put in place is, on the whole, weak. In this context, a policy of top-down reorganisation of services to fit a particular model of integrated care would be counter-productive. This is why the D
[normal]epartment is committed to supporting health and social care organisations to work together to develop local models of integrated care that work for them, by removing barriers, sharing tools and innovations, and helping to build the evidence base of what wo
[normal]rks locally.
[normal]83
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government has a range of policies to support local integration:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]84
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These policies have created an environment that supports local innovation and cooperation, but the Government agrees with the Health Select Committee that more needs to be done to 
[normal]drive a real step change in the integration of health and care services.
[normal]85
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This is why, as part of this year’s spending round, the Government announced 
[normal]the establishment of the Integration Transformation Fund (ITF) 
[normal]in 2015–16. The ITF breaks new ground in dr
[normal]iving local integration by ensuring that at least £3.8
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n is placed into locally controlled pooled budgets, for use across the health and social care system.
[normal]86
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To ensure that this money is spent in a truly integrated way, it will only be released to are
[normal]as that have jointly agreed plans, signed off by the CCG and the local authority, for how the funding will be used. These plans will reflect a local approach to integrated care, but must also contain some key enablers that we believe are essential, includi
[normal]ng:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]87
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The planning process will 
[normal]for the first time bring commissioners from health and social care together to make real decisions about priorities and spending across organisational boundaries. This will have benefits beyond the ITF itself, as plans for this fund will need to be made in
[normal] parallel to, and aligned with, plans for spending the rest of the social care and health budgets. More than ever before, commissioners on both sides will need to be aware of the whole health and social care system. Local authorities and CCGs will also be 
[normal]free to add further money into the pooled budget beyond their share of the £3.8
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n.
[normal]88
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A 
[normal]£1b
[normal]illio
[normal]n 
[normal]portion 
[normal]of the ITF money will be linked to performance against agreed outcome goals, which could include things like reducing delayed transfers of care or 
[normal]improving patient experience. This will create shared incentives for improvement and require local partners to work closely together to focus on the outcomes that they are seeking
[normal].
[normal]89
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department is working with NHS England, the LGA and colleagues from acr
[normal]oss central government to finalise the details of how the ITF will work in practice. Detailed guidance for CCGs and 
[normal]l
[normal]ocal 
[normal]a
[normal]uthorities, and details of how the funding will be allocated, will be published later 
[normal]in 2013 
[normal]alongside NHS planning guidance and the
[normal] local government settlement.
[normal]90
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All areas will then need to agree plans early next year for how the fund will be used. These plans will cover two years, with 2014
[normal]–15
[normal] used to prepare for the introduction of the pooled budgets and make early progress on priori
[normal]ties. To ensure that social care services have the resources to do this, 
[normal]as additional £200 million 
[normal]ha
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]been 
[normal]announced 
[normal]for 
[normal]transfer from the NHS to local authorities in 2014
[normal]–15
[normal] for social care with a health benefit.
[normal]91
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Some of these changes will require legis
[normal]lation and 
[normal]the Department is 
[normal] seek
[normal]ing
[normal] to make the necessary provisions through the Care Bill.
[normal]4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]FUNDING[bold]4.1[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The effectiveness of the mechanisms by which resources are distributed geographically in the NHS[bold]92
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 2012 Health and Social Care Act establishes a new financial landscape with key financial decisions and monitoring to take place 
[normal]variously 
[normal]in the Department, NHS England, Monitor and the
[normal] 
[normal]TDA. These organisations need to work together to ensure that the 
[normal]best outcomes are 
[normal]consistently 
[normal]delivered for patients and the public whil
[normal]e
[normal] securing value for money and 
[normal]remaining within the total Department of Health 
[normal]DEL
[normal] provided by HM Treasury.
[normal]93
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to achieve this a 
[normal]S
[normal]hared 
[normal]Financial Planning Agreement board 
[normal] has b
[normal]een established between the key organisations in the new system.  The key underlying principle is that each organisation remains responsible and accountable for financial decisions as set out in the Act but in addition will work together to establish a com
[normal]mon agreement over the 
[normal]key 
[normal]financial parameters that form the foundation of each organisation’s financial planning.
[normal]94
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This co-operation is intended to achieve a number of objectives:
[normal]95
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to deliver these
[normal] objectives:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]96
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Agreement on the key financial parameters will need t
[normal]o be reached ahead of the start of each financial year.  The usual planning cycle is that this would be done by the end of each calendar year.
[normal]97
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The final decision on the overall disposition of funding between 
[normal]c
[normal]ommissioners (NHS England), other 
[normal]a
[normal]rm
[normal]’
[normal]s
[normal]-l
[normal]ength 
[normal]b
[normal]odies and 
[normal]that 
[normal]held centrally is made by the Secretary of State, informed by recommendations of the Shared Finan
[normal]cial Planning Agreement 
[normal]b
[normal]oard.
[normal]98
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chart 
[normal]1
[normal] illustrates the flow of revenue resource funds in 2013–14, extrapolated from the actual flow of funds in
[normal] 2012–13.  The chart figures are illustrative and are based on the planned allocations and forecasts of the sectors within the Department of Health group for 2013–14. The level of funds flows or intra group trading for 2013–14 between the different sectors
[normal] within the group has been estimated, based on 2012–13 data. They are intended to illustrate how the financial transfers within the group work; they are not and are not intended to be a projection of the actual financial performance in 2013–14.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chart 
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]99
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he bulk of 
[normal]revenue resource 
[normal]funding is allocated to NHS England
[normal]:
[normal] no funding is 
[normal]a
[normal]llocated direct to the provider sector.  Instead, the provider sector receives all 
[normal]revenue 
[normal]funding through their trading a
[normal]rr
[normal]angements.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]NHS England’s allocations to CCGs[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]100
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 2012 Act that created NHS England also makes it independently responsible for allocating the budgets for commissioning NHS services. This was done to prevent any perception of political interference in the
[normal] way that money is distributed between different parts of the country, although the Mandate can set out the high level aims for the allocation process.  The current mandate, for instance, requires the allocation of resources to have regard to equal access 
[normal]for equal need, draw on independent advice and take account of the importance of stable funding.  Allocation decisions also need to be consistent with NHS England’s legal duties, in particular to have regard to equality of access to and outcomes from healt
[normal]hcare.
[normal]101
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Assessing the effectiveness of allocation decisions is challenging. For instance, it is difficult to isolate the marginal effect of more or less funding on outcomes.  Also, managers strive to manage to their allocations, meaning that the allocations
[normal] are only one factor in determining the financ
[normal]ial health of an organisation.
[normal]102
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The design of the process for reaching decisions is therefore critical in delivering a financial allocation that is as effective as possible.  NHS England has adopted an allocatio
[normal]n process that has clear objectives, uses the best independent advice and places reliance on evidence-based approaches complemented by judgement where appropriate.  These are all features that have been preserved from the previous PCT allocation process an
[normal]d which the Public Accounts Committee supported during their landscape review of allocations process across the public sector.
[normal]103
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]At their December 2012 meeting the NHS England board expressed concerns that the proposed target formula for the allocation of re
[normal]sources to CCGs, developed in partnership with the Advisory Committee on Resource Allocation
[normal] (ACRA)
[normal] , if implemented alone, would have led to a greater targeting of resources towards areas with better health outcomes, although in practice this would have b
[normal]een mitigated by pace-of-change decisions. They therefore decided to give each CCG the same growth in programme funding for 2013
[normal]–14
[normal], giving time to review further the appro
[normal]ach to allocation of resources.
[normal]104
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]At the same time NHS England announced a Fundamental
[normal] Review of Allocations, with initial findings being available to influence the approach for 2014
[normal]–15
[normal].  This covers the local allocation of resources across the full range of NHS England responsibilities, including both allocations to CCGs and the budgets av
[normal]ailable for direct commissioning functions.
[normal]105
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]r
[normal]eview undertook to develop the underlying philosophy for the high
[normal]-
[normal]level split between commissioning streams and the linkages between them, including, as part of its longer term objectives, an understanding o
[normal]f the impact of spending on outcomes.
[normal]106
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The key aim of the formula is equal access for equal need. The formulae must facilitate a ‘fair share’ distribution of resources across the country in proportion to need. In addition, NHS England must ensure that the a
[normal]llocation of funding does not cause any destabilising effect on local health economies.
[normal]107
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Local allocations are based around four key decisions:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]108
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]With respect to the CCG fair-shares formula (covering £63.4
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n or 66% of NHS England Mandate funding in 2013
[normal]–14
[normal]), a detailed review of the performance of the formula has been undertaken with recommendations as to whet
[normal]her the aims of the formula require amendment to reflect NHS England’s strategies for outcome improvement and inequality reduction, and if so, how this can be achieved in an evidence-based manner.
[normal]109
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In determining need, the formula applies a person-based app
[normal]roach, taking in to account:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]110
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The approach proposed by ACRA is based on current u
[normal]tilisation of services: due to data constraints, this is based on hospital utilisation data rather than health services more broadly.  This is then adjusted for factors that affect utilisation, but are not linked to need, such as proximity to a provider.  
[normal]However, this still leaves a possible gap in estimating need where need is systematically unmet.  This is recognised as one of the key challenges for a utilisation based model.
[normal]111
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Prior to 2013
[normal]–14
[normal], a further adjustment for health inequalities and unmet need w
[normal]as applied to the PCT allocations formula to redistribute 10% of total funding based on the 
[normal]d
[normal]isability
[normal]-f
[normal]ree 
[normal]l
[normal]ife 
[normal]e
[normal]xpectancy (DFLE),  the number of years someone might expect to live without a long term
[normal],
[normal] limiting illness. ACRA  has recommended that any adju
[normal]stment for unmet need should be based on the standardised mortality ratio for those under 75 years (SMR&lt;75), which indicates how many more or fewer deaths there are in each area compared with the national average after allowing the different age structures
[normal] in each area. ACRA regards SMR&lt;75 as a significantly more robust metric to use for this purpose, and this would bring the approach to CCG allocations in line with that used in public health. A judgement is required as to whether such an adjustment is appr
[normal]opriate and, if so, what quantum to apply, and options on the inclusion of an adjustment based on SMR&lt;75 are to be put to the NHS England 
[normal]b
[normal]oard.
[normal]112
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In August 2013, NHS England published initial estimates of the ‘target’ allocations for CCGs based on the ACRA 
[normal]recommendations, to support engagement with NHS, 
[normal]l
[normal]ocal 
[normal]a
[normal]uthority colleagues, and other stakeholders. This publication reflected the original formula and current spending estimates considered at the board in December 2012, and did not include any of the fur
[normal]ther adjustments for unmet need or inequalities that are currently being considered.  Four regional workshops were held to gather views and inform robust decisions on resource allocation.
[normal]113
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]One of the key aims of the workshops was to inform judgements NHS En
[normal]gland will have to make around pace-of-change: what the most appropriate balance is between moving resources to reflect need and protecting current levels of funding to protect the stability of commissioners and providers.  It is tempting to assume in the 
[normal]current context of resource constraint that setting aside the target estimates and giving all CCGs the same growth may be the fairest solution.  However, this takes no account of rapid population rises and declines that, if ignored, could drive some areas 
[normal]in to financial distress.
[normal]114
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I
[normal]n setting its allocation policy NHS England has to demonstrate that the policy does not destabilise local health economies.   Initial analysis of estimates of ‘target’ allocations for CCGs appears to indicate a strong link betwee
[normal]n ‘underfunding’ and both CCGs currently at risk of deficit and local health economies with deficit trusts.
[normal]115
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Of the 13 CCGs reporting a 2013
[normal]–14
[normal] forecast deficit in August
[normal] 2013
[normal], 11 are below their ‘target’ allocations. The average distance from target of tho
[normal]se 13 CCGS is 3.21% or £11.3
[normal] 
[normal]m
[normal]illion
[normal] under target. A total of 42 providers are identified as in deficit at 
[normal]quarter 
[normal]1, 17 Foundation Trusts and 25 non-FT providers. 
[normal]Thirty
[normal] of the 42 relevant commissioning CCGs (or groups of CCGs) mapped to these providers a
[normal]re under target allocations by an average of 2.27% or £11.8
[normal] 
[normal]m
[normal]illion
[normal].
[normal]116
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]NHS England is currently developing and analysing the evidence base for ‘pace of change’ decisions and considering options for, and implications of, potential multi-year allocations from 
[normal]2014
[normal]–15.
[normal]117
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is proposed that resources for 
[normal]p
[normal]rimary 
[normal]c
[normal]are, covering primary medical services (GPs), dental care, pharmaceutical services and ophthalmology services and totalling £11.1
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illio
[normal]n in 2013
[normal]–14
[normal], should be set through separate formulae. For the 
[normal]largest element, primary medical services, an allocation based on the Carr-Hill formula is proposed. This is largely based on need, reflecting the number of patients registered and age-gender mix of the practice, as well as factors related to the health st
[normal]atus of the population.  These factors could be regarded as a proxy for inequalities but there is no specific additional adjustment for deprivation or inequalities in the base formula which has been developed. Distinct formulae have been developed for dent
[normal]al services, based on an age-cost curve by deprivation index for those accessing NHS dental care, and pharmaceutical services, which uses the prescribing formula used in CCG allocations as a proxy for the cost of community pharmacy services.
[normal]118
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Current NHS En
[normal]gland strategy is to increase the proportion of funding routed through the Global Sum starting with the phasing out of MPIG
[normal] (minimum practice income guarantee)
[normal]. This over time will better align funding to need.
[normal]119
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Specialised services are nationally commissio
[normal]ned to a common standard.  Area 
[normal]T
[normal]eams have a relationship with providers in their area, rather than providing services for a specific population.  Resources are therefore determined by patient referrals (reflecting need) and constrained at national level r
[normal]ather than being subject to local allocations.
[normal]4.2[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Financial pressures in the system, such as funding for general practice, and for A&amp;E services.[bold]120
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The final funding that goes to 
[normal]providers, including 
[normal]gen
[normal]eral practice and A&amp;E services
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]is 
[normal]generally 
[normal]determined 
[normal]by local commissioning arrangements via CCGs
[normal] and 
[normal]Public Health England (see 
[normal]c
[normal]hart 
[normal]1
[normal], section 
[normal]4.1)
[normal].
[normal]121
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As part of discussions on overall funding,  analysis of pressures across the whole system are assessed by the Shared Financial Planning 
[normal]Agreement 
[normal]b
[normal]oard
[normal].
[normal]122
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Different priorities 
[normal]need to be funded from the resource 
[normal]growth 
[normal]available 
[normal]to the NHS. 
[normal]Pressures 
[normal]are grouped into three categories:
[normal]123
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unit cost 
[normal]pressures cover the cost of m
[normal]eeting existing commitments that are essential for delivery of NHS services. They do not cover underlying 
[normal]demand, or increased levels of activity, which may arise due to demographic pressures or medical advance. Service developments are new areas of activi
[normal]ty which arise due to new 
[normal]strategies, 
[normal]polic
[normal]ies 
[normal]and priorities
[normal].
[normal]124
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]H
[normal]ospital and community health service (H
[normal]CHS
[normal])
[normal] pay bill pressures are the largest component of the 
[normal]unit cost 
[normal]pressures and usually form the first call on NHS resources. Managing 
[normal]these 
[normal]pressures 
[normal]effectively allows the NHS to treat a growing ageing population whil
[normal]e
[normal] making best use of the funding available.
